  "prompt": "Can I create a database application with C#?",
  "response": "Yes, absolutely! C# provides multiple ways to create database applications:\n\n1. ADO.NET\n- Traditional .NET database access\n- Low-level database connectivity\n- Works with various database systems\n- Manual data handling\n\nExample:\n```csharp\nusing System.Data.SqlClient;\n\nstring connectionString = \"Server=myServerAddress;Database=myDataBase;User Id=myUsername;Password=myPassword;\";\nSqlConnection connection = new SqlConnection(connectionString);\nSqlCommand command = new SqlCommand(\"SELECT * FROM Customers\", connection);\n```\n\n2. Entity Framework\n- Object-Relational Mapping (ORM)\n- Simplified database interactions\n- Code-first or database-first approaches\n- Supports multiple database providers\n\nExample:\n```csharp\npublic class ApplicationDbContext : DbContext\n{\n    public DbSet<Customer> Customers { get; set; }\n}\n\n// Querying data\nvar customers = context.Customers.Where(c => c.City == \"New York\");\n```\n\n3. Dapper\n- Lightweight ORM\n- High performance\n- Simple database access\n- Supports multiple databases\n\nExample:\n```csharp\nvar customers = connection.Query<Customer>(\"SELECT * FROM Customers\");\n```\n\n4. Windows Forms/WPF Applications\n- Create database-driven desktop applications\n- Data binding\n- Visual database interactions\n\nThese approaches offer flexibility for different database application needs.",
